## ❓ Common Judge Questions & Strong Answers

**Q: Why did you use Dijkstra and not BFS?**
> BFS finds the path with the fewest edges, but not the shortest physical distance. Dijkstra uses weighted edges (Euclidean distance between x,y coordinates), so it finds the path that minimizes actual walking distance.

**Q: How does the system know the layout of the station?**
> Each station's layout is hardcoded as a graph (nodes + edges) in the backend [main.py](file:///c:/Users/Praveen/OneDrive/Desktop/navisphere-railway-station-resource-tracker-main/backend/main.py). Each node has an (x, y) percentage coordinate matching the station blueprint image. The edges define which locations are physically connected.

**Q: What happens if no path exists?**
> The algorithm returns `None`. The backend sends a 404 error JSON response, and the frontend shows an alert to the user.

**Q: Why FastAPI and not Node.js?**
> Python is excellent for algorithms. FastAPI is faster than Flask and has built-in data validation with Pydantic. For this type of computation-heavy backend, Python is a natural choice.

**Q: Could this scale to more stations?**
> Yes. Adding a new station just means adding a new entry in the `STATION_GRAPHS` dictionary in [main.py](file:///c:/Users/Praveen/OneDrive/Desktop/navisphere-railway-station-resource-tracker-main/backend/main.py) and a corresponding entry in [stations.js](file:///c:/Users/Praveen/OneDrive/Desktop/navisphere-railway-station-resource-tracker-main/frontend/src/data/stations.js) in the frontend. No other code changes needed.

**Q: What is CORS and why is it in your code?**
> CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) is a browser security rule that blocks a webpage from calling a different server. The React frontend runs on port 5173 and our API is on port 8000. Without the CORS middleware, every API call would be blocked by the browser. We configured it to allow all origins during development.

**Q: Why use React-Konva for the map?**
> The station maps are PNG images. We need to draw interactive dots and lines on top of them at specific coordinates. HTML elements can't do this precisely. Konva is a Canvas library that lets us render shapes, images, and event handlers all in one canvas — perfect for this use case.

**Q: What are Waypoints?**
> Waypoints are invisible routing nodes in the graph. They represent real physical structures like stair landings or bridge midpoints that the algorithm needs to route through, but that we don't want cluttering the map UI. They're marked `isHidden: true` in the frontend and filtered out from the dropdown selectors.

